## Types of Wristbands

The realm of personal adornment, particularly around the wrist, has seen a curious evolution, encompassing everything from the intricate artistry of [braided friendship bracelets](/Friendship_bracelet) to the deceptively simple modern iteration: the gel bracelet. While the former often carries sentimental weight, woven with care and intent, the latter presents a more ephemeral, yet equally potent, statement.

### Gel Bracelets

[Gel bracelets](/Wristband), often interchangeably referred to as jelly bracelets, represent a distinct category of [wristband](/Wristband), predominantly crafted from [silicone](/Silicone). Their design is typically straightforward, featuring either a rectangular or circular cross-section, lending them a clean, unembellished aesthetic. These accessories are characterized by their inherent stretchiness, allowing for a comfortable, one-size-fits-most application, and are produced in an almost infinite spectrum of colors. [^1]

Their popularity isn't a continuous, unwavering phenomenon, but rather a series of distinct waves that have swept across the [Western world](/Western_world) and beyond since the 1980s. [^2] Each resurgence has seen them adopted by different demographics and imbued with new cultural meanings, a testament to their adaptable simplicity. From neon hues signaling youthful rebellion to more muted tones representing solidarity, these seemingly innocuous bands have consistently found a place on wrists, reflecting prevailing trends and underlying social currents.

### Charity Awareness Wristbands

The humble gel bracelet underwent a significant transformation, ascending from mere fashion accessory to a potent symbol of social consciousness, largely popularized for [charity purposes](/Charitable_organization) by the [Livestrong](/Livestrong_wristband) wristbands. The example often cited, with a hint of dark humor, is the reference to the 2010 Tonight Show conflict, which, while tangential, points to the broader cultural impact and recognition these bands achieved.

At their core, [awareness bracelet](/Awareness_ribbon) wristbands serve as a visible declaration of the wearer's support for a specific [cause](/Social_movement) or [charitable organization](/Charitable_organization). [^3] [^4] This particular application of the [silicone](/Silicone) wristband gained unprecedented traction in 2004 with the debut of the iconic yellow [Livestrong](/Livestrong_wristband) band. This initiative was spearheaded by American cyclist [Lance Armstrong](/Lance_Armstrong) through his foundation, with the explicit goal of raising public awareness and funds for [cancer](/Cancer) research and patient support. [^5] The sheer ubiquity of the bright yellow band became a global phenomenon, demonstrating the remarkable power of a simple, wearable token to galvanize support and foster a sense of collective purpose.

Following the immense success of the original [Livestrong](/Livestrong_wristband) design, a slightly larger variant, typically 1-inch (25 mm) wide, began to gain traction around 2007. These broader bands found particular favor within the music industry, where musical groups would sell them as merchandise to young concert attendees, often featuring band names or tour dates. This commercial adoption further cemented the gel bracelet's place in youth culture, extending its reach beyond purely charitable endeavors.

These wristbands are frequently perceived by younger generations as a more contemporary and stylish alternative to traditional charity pins or badges. Their appeal lies in their understated integration into everyday attire, offering a subtle yet clear statement of affiliation. Furthermore, the economic practicality of these wristbands has made them an invaluable tool for fundraising efforts. Both the wider and thinner styles are remarkably inexpensive to custom manufacture in bulk, allowing [charitable organizations](/Charitable_organization) to acquire them at a minimal cost and sell them at a reasonable price, typically around $1 or £1. [^6] [^7] The vast majority of the proceeds generated from these sales are then channeled directly towards the designated charity or cause, making them an efficient and accessible method for both raising funds and increasing public visibility for critical issues.

### Urban Legend of Sex Bracelets

*See also: [Handkerchief code](/Handkerchief_code)*

In a rather predictable turn of events for any widely adopted youth accessory, a resurgence in the popularity of gel bracelets around 2003 saw them become entangled in a pervasive [urban legend](/Urban_legend). This legend, linking the innocent bands to a supposed sex game, quickly spread, explaining their sudden, intense popularity among young teenagers. Consequently, these accessories were rather infamously dubbed "sex bracelets." [^2] [^8] [^9] [^10]

The core of the legend asserted that different colors of the bracelet were coded to represent various sex acts, implying either that the wearer had already performed these acts or, more provocatively, was willing to perform them. The most common and widely circulated version of this narrative claimed that if someone managed to break a bracelet a wearer had on, the wearer was then obligated to perform the sex act associated with that particular color. [^11] This alarming rumor gained significant traction in the United States in 2003, and by the close of the decade, during a subsequent wave of media attention, it had proliferated globally, proving that human credulity knows no borders. [^12]

The genesis of the "sex bracelet" [urban legend](/Urban_legend) can be meticulously traced back to the autumn of 2003. An early entry for the term "shag band" appeared on [Urban Dictionary](/Urban_Dictionary) in September of that year, indicating the nascent stages of the rumor's linguistic formalization. By October, newspapers in North Carolina and Florida were already reporting on schools implementing bans on the bracelets, citing concerns over disruption and inappropriate comments. Concurrently, *[Time](/Time_(magazine))* magazine ran an article addressing the burgeoning phenomenon. [^13] The rumors had become so prominent by October 2003 that the principal of Alachua Elementary School in [Gainesville, Florida](/Gainesville,_Florida), felt compelled to ban the bracelets outright to prevent further disruption and to curtail the inappropriate discussions they were generating among students. [^14] This initial ban was swiftly followed by similar prohibitions in other schools across Florida and various other regions. [^2] It is noteworthy that the administrators imposing these early bans generally did not insinuate that the rumors themselves were factual. However, some later media reports, reflecting on the widespread panic, suggested that these bans and the accompanying media sensationalism may have inadvertently fueled a [moral panic](/Moral_panic) rather than merely responding to a genuine threat. [^15] [^10] [^16] The British press, ever keen to report on the perceived moral decay of youth, began to detail the supposed meanings of the bands' colors in 2005. [^17]

An interesting, albeit unrelated, parallel can be drawn to the [Countrywide Financial Corporation](/Countrywide_Financial_Corporation)'s "Loyalty oath" bracelet. [^18] In 2007, the stark consequence of not signing such a loyalty oath was, rather explicitly, to "lose my job." [^19] This demonstrates how simple wristbands, in vastly different contexts, can become symbols of obligation or consequence, however misguided.

Similar sensational stories resurfaced in the British media in 2009, where the bracelets were allegedly known by the rather less subtle moniker of "shag bands." [^20] [^21] Concurrently, and perhaps illustrating the global reach of teenage folklore, analogous narratives circulated extensively throughout Brazil during the 2009/2010 summer, with the bracelets being referred to locally as "pulseiras do sexo." [^22] Tragically, in March 2010, this [urban legend](/Urban_legend) took a horrific turn when a 13-year-old girl in Brazil was raped by three teenage boys after one of them forcibly snatched a bracelet she was wearing. Police investigators subsequently stated that the heinous crime was motivated by the pervasive belief in the "sex bracelets" legend. [^23]

Different iterations of this [urban legend](/Urban_legend) assigned varying sexual acts to specific colors, echoing the long-standing, albeit distinct, tradition of the [handkerchief code](/Handkerchief_code). [^24] For instance, purple might be associated with kissing, red with a [lap dance](/Lap_dance), and black, almost universally, with sexual intercourse. [^10] [^15] The sheer inconsistency in these color-act associations across different reports is a hallmark of [urban legends](/Urban_legend). Sociologists Joel Best and Kathleen Bogle, in their meticulous research, uncovered a staggering 193 distinct lists of color–sex act pairings, encompassing 48 different colors. Their findings revealed that while some colors enjoyed a relatively wide consensus regarding their supposed meanings – black, for example, was almost invariably linked to sexual intercourse – others were far more ambiguous. For instance, while [cunnilingus](/Fellatio) was the most common act associated with the color green, fewer than half of the sources that included green actually assigned it this meaning, highlighting the arbitrary and decentralized nature of the legend's propagation. [^25]

Some versions of the legend posited that the indicated sexual activity would occur at specific parties organized for that purpose, making them eerily similar to contemporary rumors surrounding "[rainbow parties](/Rainbow_party_(sexuality))"—gatherings where girls, supposedly wearing varying shades of [lipstick](/Lipstick), would take turns [fellating](/Fellatio) their male counterparts, leaving a colorful array on their penises. Such tales of teenage [sex parties](/Group_sex) have, regrettably, circulated at various points throughout history, reflecting persistent anxieties about adolescent sexuality. Folklorist Barbara Mikkelson of [snopes](/Snopes).com, a renowned authority on [urban legends](/Urban_legend), draws a clear association between the "sex bracelet" stories and similar narratives from previous decades. In the 1970s, for example, pull tabs from [aluminum cans](/Beverage_can) and labels from [beer bottles](/Beer_bottle) were supposedly considered "sex coupons," obligating any girl presented with one to sleep with the bearer. By the 1990s, these rumors had simply shifted focus to include an assortment of plastic items, some of which were worn as bracelets. [^2] Best and Bogle suggest a parallel to the children's game of [kiss chase](/Kiss_chase), where pursuit implies a right to a kiss, a rather disturbing evolution from playground antics to alleged sexual coercion. [^26] According to Mikkelson, there is likely very little, if any, truth behind these sensational stories, and the vast majority of teenagers who have contacted her site express genuine shock and profound disappointment that so many adults and peers have actually believed them, a sentiment that speaks volumes about the enduring power of rumor.

### MY Single Band

The concept of the gel bracelet even extended into the realm of relationship status, with at least one specific type, known as the MY Single Band, being explicitly designed to advertise the wearer's availability. [^27] [^28] The reception to this particular bracelet, however, was largely critical, bordering on derisive. Natasha Burton, writing for *[Cosmopolitan](/Cosmopolitan_(magazine))*, expressed considerable skepticism, noting that she doubted men would actively seek out such a bracelet, particularly given that she was still approached even while conspicuously wearing her [engagement ring](/Engagement_ring). [^29] The editorial staff of *[Glamour](/Glamour_(magazine))*, a publication generally attuned to fashion and social trends, reportedly found the entire concept rather uncomfortable and misguided. [^30] Eliana Dockterman of *[Time](/Time_(magazine))* magazine delivered perhaps the most pointed critique, comparing the act of wearing such a band to the absurdity of displaying one's [OkCupid](/OkCupid) profile directly on their [T-shirt](/T-shirt), effectively reducing a complex personal status to a reductive, publicly broadcasted label. [^28] The general consensus was that while the idea aimed for clarity, it ultimately missed the mark on both social nuance and practical efficacy.

